---
layout: layout-base.njk
title: US Cities With the Highest Growing Degree Days | GrowByDate
description: Compare U.S. cities by base 50°F growing degree day accumulation for warm-season crop planning.
canonical: "https://growbydate.com/data/rankings/us-cities-with-the-highest-growing-degree-days/"
datasetSchema:
  dateModified: "2026-06-07"
  spatialCoverage: "United States"
  temporalCoverage: "Long-term climate planning normals"
  variableMeasured:
    - "Base 50°F growing degree days"
    - "Seasonal heat accumulation"
    - "City rank"
  measurementTechnique: "U.S. city ranking by seasonal base-50°F growing degree day accumulation."
  keywords:
    - "garden climate ranking"
    - "frost-free days"
    - "growing degree days"
    - "short-season gardening"
  distributionName: "Us Cities With The Highest Growing Degree Days"
---

{% set board = usCitiesHighestGdd %}
{% set top = board.top %}

<section class="card leaderboardHero">
  <p class="eyebrow">City comparison</p>
  <h1>US Cities With the Highest Growing Degree Days</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    Frost dates tell you how long the outdoor window is. Growing degree days help explain how much heat accumulates inside that window.
    This ranking compares U.S. cities by base 50°F GDD, a useful reference point for warm-season crop planning.
  </p>

  <div class="leaderboardStatGrid" aria-label="Ranking summary">
    {% if top %}
      <div class="leaderboardStat">
        <span class="statLabel">Highest GDD</span>
        <strong>{{ top.cityName }}</strong>
        <span>{{ top.gddBase50 }} base 50°F GDD · {{ top.label }}</span>
      </div>
    {% endif %}

    <div class="leaderboardStat">
      <span class="statLabel">Cities compared</span>
      <strong>{{ board.entries.length }}</strong>
      <span>U.S. cities with GDD values</span>
    </div>

    <div class="leaderboardStat">
      <span class="statLabel">Best used for</span>
      <strong>Warm-season crops</strong>
      <span>Tomatoes, peppers, corn, squash, cucumbers, melons, okra, and sweet potatoes</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>The ranking</h2>
  <p>
    Cities are ranked by base 50°F growing degree day accumulation. Higher values usually mean more seasonal heat for warm-season crops,
    but water, heat stress, frost timing, and variety choice still matter.
  </p>

  <div class="tableWrap leaderboardTableWrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Rank</th>
          <th>City</th>
          <th>Base 50°F GDD</th>
          <th>Base 45°F GDD</th>
          <th>Base 40°F GDD</th>
          <th>Heat read</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {% for row in board.entries %}
          <tr>
            <td><strong>#{{ row.rank }}</strong></td>
            <td>
              <a href="{{ row.url }}"><strong>{{ row.cityName }}</strong></a><br>
              <span class="small muted">{{ row.regionName }}, U.S.</span>
            </td>
            <td><strong>{{ row.gddBase50 }}</strong></td>
            <td>{{ row.gddBase45 if row.gddBase45 != null else "—" }}</td>
            <td>{{ row.gddBase40 if row.gddBase40 != null else "—" }}</td>
            <td>{{ row.label }}</td>
          </tr>
        {% endfor %}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card leaderboardCallout">
  <h2>What this ranking means</h2>
  <p>
    A city with more base 50°F GDD generally has more heat available for warm-season crops. In the hottest U.S. locations,
    that can also mean heat stress, drought pressure, or irrigation needs become part of the gardening picture.
  </p>
  <p>
    Compare with <a href="/data/rankings/us-cities-with-the-longest-growing-seasons/">US Cities With the Longest Growing Seasons</a>
    and the full <a href="/data/growing-degree-days-by-city/">Growing Degree Days by City</a> reference.
  </p>
</section>

{% set sourceLinksVariant = "gdd" %}
{% set sourceLinksId = "ranking-us-cities-with-the-highest-growing-degree-days" %}
{% set sourceLinksHeading = "Official source context for this ranking" %}
{% set sourceLinksIntro = "This ranking is a GrowByDate interpretation of frost, seasonal heat, crop margin, and timing signals. These links show the official source concepts behind the derived metrics." %}
{% include "components/external-source-links.njk" %}

<section class="card">
  <h2>Methodology</h2>
  <p>{{ board.methodology }}</p>
  <p>{{ board.caveat }}</p>
  <p class="small">
    Download: <a href="/assets/data/rankings/us-cities-with-the-highest-growing-degree-days.json">highest U.S. growing degree days JSON</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "ItemList",
  "name": {{ board.title | dump | safe }},
  "description": {{ board.description | dump | safe }},
  "url": "https://growbydate.com/data/rankings/us-cities-with-the-highest-growing-degree-days/",
  "numberOfItems": {{ board.entries.length }},
  "itemListElement": [
    {% for row in board.entries %}
      {
        "@type": "ListItem",
        "position": {{ row.rank }},
        "name": {{ (row.cityName ~ " base 50°F growing degree days") | dump | safe }},
        "url": {{ (site.url ~ row.url) | dump | safe }}
      }{% if not loop.last %},{% endif %}
    {% endfor %}
  ]
}
</script>
